sentences: Valery Alexandrovich Kipelov (Russian: Валерий Александрович Кипелов; born July 12, 1958) is a Russian musician and composer who was the vocalist and a founding member of heavy metal band Aria.
Since 2002, Kipelov leads his own metal band, Kipelov.
Kipelov was born in 1958 in Kapotnya, Moscow, Soviet Union.
After military service in 1978–1980 Kipelov joined the folk ensemble Shestero Molodykh ("Six Young Men"), where he met an befriended Nikolay Rastorguev.
In September 1980, Kipelov and Rastorguev continued their career in Leysa, Pyesnya ("Go on, Song").
In 1985, the band was officially disbanded due to failing to complete the planned program.
After the breakup in 1987, Kipelov and Holstinin were the only two members who remained with their producer Vekshtein.
During the Germany tour 1994, Kipelov's relations with Holstinin and Dubinin became tense.
In 1997 they released the LP entitled Kipelov and Mavrin - Smutnoye Vremia (Time of Troubles), which included ten tracks.

In 2002, after the successful release of 'Himera' followed by sold-out tours and headlining the NASHEstvie festival, Kipelov refused to start recording the new album, already written by Dubinin and Holstinin.
This disagreement broke Aria apart after 'Judgement Day', August 31, 2002.

On September 1, 2002, the day after Kipelov left Aria, Kipelov, Terentyev, Mavrin and Maniakin launched a new band named Kipelov (named at Terentyev's suggestion as the bandmembers couldn't come up with any better name).
In 2003, they released the live album Put Naverh (Way to the Top), recorded in Saint Petersburg.
From 2002 to 2005, the only new release was the EP Babylon.
Kipelov's first LP, 'Reki Vremen' (Rivers of Time), came out in 2005.
They have two children: Janna (b. 1980, a music conductor), and Alexander (b. 1989, a student of the Cello at Gnesin School).

The ballad "Ya Svoboden" (I am Free) became a top hit in the Russian rock charts.
Terentyev, and later Mavrin, left Kipelov in the next two years, explaining that the band was too slow in releasing the new album.
